segments.text: There was, I would say a girl, only she was a little older than a girl, but somebody that I had taught that one year.
She came back to Brady and lived with a lady that lived just behind me.
And she came over one day.
It must have been early August of 45.
And I'd been hearing from Earl from Le Havre, which was a place where they shipped them home from.
And she said, you've just got to go with me.
See, she married a New Yorker, and she had the car.
And he was back, and he wanted her to get on up there.
And so.
I remember calling my parents and seeing if they would keep the two children.
They said, yeah.
So they came and got them.
We left the next day and drove nonstop to New York City.
And by then, she said that she hadn't been able to get anybody to ride with her.
But by the time we left, there was a young man who was in the Navy.
But we all knew him from high school.
He early coached him.
And a young woman that we didn't know, but her husband was in the Navy up there somewhere.
So there were four of us.
And we saved the one young man for the night driving.
And then we'd take turns sitting next to him so we'd keep him awake.
And the other young woman didn't know how to drive.
So the owner of the car and I did the daytime driving.
And the only thing I can remember about that, I don't know how much gasoline was, a gallon.
But we each put $10 in the pot, the ones that didn't own the car, to buy gas.
And agreed that if that ran out, we'd put some more in.
But it never ran out.
We got all the way to New York City on $30 worth of gas.
And we were to meet her husband in Grand Central Station, my friend Alice, who had insisted that I stay with her.
So she was down there to meet us.
It's amazing how we even knew how to find that place.
Right now, when did he get there?
Okay, nine days later.
And during that time, the 6th of August, they dropped the atomic bomb.
I thought, hmm, they dropped the bomb.
Didn't mean anything to me.
I was waiting for my husband to come home.
No, I didn't take much notice of that at all.
But it's funny how I got in touch with somebody that could...
tell me what to do and what not to do.
In Menard, there was a man that owned the theater there.
And his name was Henry Reeves.
He was not like anybody else in Menard.
Well, he's got a really good story behind him, but I won't try to tell you that.
But he had some relative.
I'm not sure whether it was a son or something else.
But he was already back home from the war.
And he'd been with the same division that Earl was with.
And it was back in Philadelphia.
And so Henry gave me his number to call him in Philadelphia.
He said, he can tell you what to do.
So when I got to New York, I called him and got him.
And he put me in touch with a Colonel Jones at the port of embarkation.
And that man had also been with the 28th Division.
So he was so helpful to me.
And he said, I know that you would like to go down and see him get off the boat.
He told me what boat he was coming in on, something I'd never heard of.
And he said, you just stay where you are, and I will let him know your number.
Well, not only did he let him know the number to reach me, he sent it to Earl 30 miles at sea.
So he knew where to get in touch.
And of course, he had no earthly idea I was even going to be in New York.
And I didn't either.
At first, we had thought about it.
But then we decided that travel was so difficult that we better not try that.
I'd meet him somewhere else.
But it worked out.
So that's what gave me my first taste of New York.
And I decided I didn't like New York.
Alice got us a reservation at the Pierre Hotel.
It's still a very fancy hotel where all the presidents and so on stay.
And I was so country, I didn't know anything.
And I had my little suitcase, and I was out on the corner waiting for a cab.
And men in New York would just elbow you out of the way if a cab came along.
I thought, I don't like this.
But anyway, I finally got down there.
It was a lovely hotel.
Describe the scene when he got off the boat and you first saw him.
I didn't see him.
He told me to stay in her apartment and he would give Earl the word of where to call me.
He also said, don't expect to see him for 24 hours because they have this debriefing or whatever.
So I was prepared not to see him, but I went on down and got in the room at the hotel.
And four o'clock, he landed about nine in the morning, and four o'clock he was at the door.
That's pretty exciting.
Hadn't seen him in two years.
Hadn't seen him in two years.
And Alice, when she was out visiting with me, she was always taking movies of the kids and whatever was going on out there.
So she had a party at her apartment and showed all those.
So Earl got to kind of catch up on what the kids were looking like, you know.
Right.
How did he appear?
That first view after the war was over compared with your memory of him before he left?
He was pretty trim.
He still weighed about 218, and yet he was just as trim because, oh, the training they had, you know.
Now, did you, as he walked or did anything, did you detect any of the effects of the injuries?
No, not at all.
And then he had a 30-day leave, and the plan was that the division was to reassemble at Camp Shelby, Mississippi.
I thought I wouldn't remember that one, but I did.
It's out of Hattiesburg.
And be sent to the Pacific Theater.
That was the plan.
But during the 30-day leave that he was at home...

war with japan ended see after dropping those atomic bombs a couple of them they gave it gave it up and so he thought that he'd just go over there and they'd say go home you know didn't work that way so he called me again won't you over here by let's see call me sunday morning i want you over here by tuesday noon because tuesday evening they have the final dinner so i had to
I was a creature of habit.
I didn't usually wash with my little ringer-type washing machine, which I had to pull over next to the sink.
I didn't wash until Monday.
But that day I did.
I washed on Sunday.
And I just took it from the ringer in a pan over to the lady that ironed for me, left that afternoon, because he wanted me there by Tuesday noon.
And I made it.
But we spent one night on the road I've forgotten where.
But he was, like I said, he was in the habit of giving orders, and he had given to me.
He wanted me somewhere at a certain time.
All right.
Then when is he discharged, or released, maybe you should say?
Well, that, I said, you know, right now, I'm writing to somebody about something.
See, for Earl's 35 years in the reserve, I get absolutely nothing.
And I shouldn't put that on this tape, but I don't care.
And any time the Army wanted anything, there wasn't any question in Earl's mind, he did it.
And while I was still over there at Camp Shelby, that's where I went for the final dinner.
And I had looked around for a place to live because I thought we might just be staying there for a while.
And when I finally found something I thought might work, he got orders from wherever.
They wanted him to be in command of a victory loan train, it was called.
Did you ever hear of that?
And it had all kinds of war souvenirs, and they'd send it around the whole United States, selling war bonds to help pay for the war.
So he didn't, that, let's see, that must have been in September.
And he didn't get home until two days before Christmas.
And it really made me mad because he'd been gone two years and he got home.
And I'd had to, you know, take care of the kids and all, everything for that length of time.
Then darned if they didn't snatch him up again.
But he never questioned anything like that.
All right.
So then he is released from active duty about the beginning of 1946.
Yeah.
And so where did you go?
In April of 1946, he was elected mayor of Brady.
I've been having some calls that there's nobody there.
I've been hoping I'd hear from Anne.
See, she's been gone a week today.
She's in France.
Oh, that's right.
She told me she was going.
And my granddaughter, I sent her.
17 years old.
She's a cutie.
Y'all moved then to Brady, and where did you live?
No, we were still in Brady.
I was already there.
Yeah.
But we bought another house.
Oh, you bought a house.
Uh-huh.
All right, and he comes back and starts to do what?
In Brady, well, he had a member of the Rangers that
he was determined that he wanted to go into business with Earl.
So as I say, Earl had this drug store, a half interest in it.
And Frank Carter was this fellow's name.
And he was an Aggie, finished in 40.
And Frank had been wounded severely in the war on D-Day.
When Frank came to see me, Frank and Elizabeth and their little girl, who was nine days younger than, older than Ann,
it suddenly made me realize what a war could do.
Because Frank had just graduated from A&M, you know, and looked good.
And when he came to see me, he had a temporary eye.
He'd lost one eye, lost all of his teeth.
On D-Day, it's a wonder he even survived.
And they put in a Goodyear and GE store.
And then they bought a service station just so they could have a place to mount the tire.
And my parents had given us our part of the ranch.
And with the ranch and two business, look after that was about all he wanted to do.
All right, so, and at that point, you were a stay-at-home mother.
Oh, yes, and adding to the family.
That's what I was going to say.
Right along.
All right, and then so he plunges into the life of the town and soon is elected mayor of Brady.
He had only been home since two days before Christmas and got elected in April.
My, my.
All right, then... His opponent was a longtime mayor, I might add.
Uh-oh, uh-oh.
Now, and everybody would agree that Brady is in the hill country, wouldn't they?
Well, yeah, at least our ranch is.
I didn't know that growing up, but somebody gave me a little pamphlet called Guide to the Texas Hill Country, and it defines exactly where it is.
And I got a map and drew it out, and I thought, well,
So both of you were then from the hill country?
I guess so.
Okay.
Now, in 1948, I understand that Mr. Rutter got involved in the U.S. Senate campaign.
Yes, he did.
Very thoroughly.
Please describe that as you remember it.
Well, Lyndon Johnson, as everybody knows, was quite a distinct character.
And I remember him coming to the House, and he said, Earl, now...
Johnson's opponent in that race was Coke Stevenson, who was a rancher on the other side of Junction, and my parents were strong for him.
They could hardly stand the idea of Earl taking over Johnson's campaign.
He wanted Earl to be his campaign manager in our district, which had about 16 or 18 counties.
And he said, now, Earl, you won't be able to carry McCulloch County, that's where Brady is, because you're too close to my opponent.
But just do the best you can with it.
And as you know, he won the statewide election by 87 votes, and they dubbed him Landslide Linden.
But when they counted the votes in McCulloch County, that county went for him by more votes than he won the statewide election.
Oh, really?
Oh.
And so from then on, Earl was his fair-haired boy.
And he had us down, they did, for a lunch at their apartment in Austin.
for a football game, and we got the experience of a wild ride across Austin with Lyndon Johnson at the wheel in a convertible.
And, oh, they just were very nice to us, and always were.
And after he became president, then, you know, it was a very opportune time.
If Earl needed help in Washington with Lyndon Johnson and Tiger Teague, he could pretty well get it.
And Jake Pickle.
And Jake Pickle, yeah.
During that campaign, what did Mr.
Rudder, what did he do?
Did he write letters, make speeches?
Yeah, and he had campaign workers in every county.
And I'll never forget, we had a dinner at Brady Country Club.
It doesn't even have food service.
So we had to get the food brought in.
And there were two women out there.
I was one of them, and then Dorothy Green from Eden, Earl's good friend's wife.
And we were over there to handle the kitchen.
And just ask the men, not their wives.
And we had about 250 acceptances and had over 300 that came.
And I could tell we were running out of food.
So we had to send in to get food.
Anyway, he was there, of course.
But then after that, gosh, back in 66,
when they were in the White House, they invited us up for a dinner for Henry Cabot Lodge.
And that was pretty exciting for me.
I'd never been in the White House at all, Earl had, because Lyndon Johnson had sent him on a fact-finding tour.
And I don't know what year that was, but it was before 66.
And just a small group of them, but Earl was to check on the educational opportunities in Vietnam.
And I do know the only female on the trip was Ovita Cup Hobby.
I've forgotten what she, but anyway, we went up for that, for the dinner for Henry Cabot Lodge.
It was very nice.
I was very impressed, because I saw so many important people that I never thought I'd see.
But you know, A&M had had, Tiger had helped so much with getting speakers for SCONA, the Student Conference on National Affairs.
I knew a lot of those because they came to this party.
Sure, sure.
What was your impression of, I presume before 1948, you did not know Mrs. Johnson, Lady Byrne?
Well, I knew her sometime.
I've got pictures with her.
What was your impression of her?
She was always very nice.
Very friendly, very nice.
I think she's top-notch.
Oh, yeah, she is.
And she's got to be patient to put up with that.
Super lady.
And, you know, I didn't know until I guess I got the battalion.
Lucy spoke at... Commencement.
Yeah, the medical school commencement.
I was surprised.
Saturday morning.
Yes.
It quoted her some, you know, what she'd said.
But I don't know.
She's going by the name of Lucy Baines Johnson again, so I don't know whether her second marriage is out or not.
I don't know.
I don't know either.
Okay, so 1948, and then so win that campaign, and y'all are still in Brady.
Yep.
And he's ranching and running the businesses.
Two businesses, yeah.
And you're adding to the number of children.
Yeah.
And then Alan Shivers.
Is it Alan Shivers that brings him to Austin?
Well, yeah.
But before that, one of the things Earl did as mayor, you know, Brady during the war had an airfield training pilots.
And
After the war was over, they deactivated it.
And Earl, I have a feeling that probably Lyndon Johnson let him know, I don't know that.
See, Earl kept a lot of things to himself.
I didn't know.
But he found out somehow from Washington that they were going to deactivate that field.
And you know, the Air Force built things pretty darn nice.
And so Earl goes to Washington.
And there's two hangars.
There's runways.
There's shops.
There's barracks.
Everything.
Earl gets the whole thing for $23,000 for Brady.
Oh, my goodness.
And anyway, it was going along fine until the labor organizers came down from Dallas and organized labor union, and then they started having strikes.
And every time they had a strike, they'd call Earl to mediate it because he knew everybody that worked out there.
And finally they just said, you just got to go to work out there to run the thing.
Well, I remember him telling me, he said, I know what I'll do.
He said, I'll just put my salary so high they won't hire me.
Because he didn't really want to.
He put his salary at $12,000 a year.
And they hired him.
That's what he was doing when he was appointed land commissioner.
All right.

and they were manufacturing wings the Martin bombers and they they employed over 800 out there and of course we were in the midst of this seven-year drought and these little these ranchers were employed at this plant kept them from going broke so it was a real good thing and during all this time you all maintained the ranch yeah your ranch
Where did he and Alan Shivers first have a connection?
Well, Earl came home from that war, and he said, War is such a terrible thing.
If you don't want it to happen again, you better get to work on the home front to keep it from happening.
So he just launched into everything.
Among things he did, he got elected to the State Democratic Executive Committee.
If you remember, Haskell, there weren't any Republicans.
Right.
Just a little handful, maybe in Dallas.
And they didn't matter.
No.
And anyway, the Democratic Party was just the same as two parties, the liberal faction and the conservative faction.
Well, Shivers and Earl, too, were conservative.
And so that's how the governor got to know Earl, was through that State Democratic Executive Committee.

and then he was elected the state board of public welfare and I don't know what all but he sure didn't want another war and so then when things fell apart you know the land office story you know that don't you now
Are you aware of who suggested or how Mr.
Rudder's name came to Alan Shivers to do that task?
I think Shivers just did it himself.
That's what I think.
See, here's the one that he succeeded.
There you go.
Yeah, Bascom Giles.
Yeah.
All right.
How did y'all, how did Shivers communicate?
That's his grandson.
He's a doctor here.
Well respected.
You know him.
Yes, yes.
Yeah, that's his grandson.
How did Governor Shivers communicate?
Oh, it shocked Earl to death.
Was it a phone call?
No.
There's a lawyer there in Brady, Ben Davis Gieselin.
I don't know if he's still a lawyer or not, but he was at UT when I was.
Anyway, he had to go to Austin for something, seeing somebody in the Capitol, and so he wanted Earl to just drive with him there.
I said, okay, said I'll.

drive with you I'll go talk to the governor and Earl had somebody in mind and I don't know who it was that he thought would be nice to appoint as land commissioner and so when he got there at the capitol he went to the governor's office and Alan Shivers was there and so when Earl said well he had an idea who somebody he might want to consider he said we've already
decided.
And Earl said, well, who?
He said, you.
Oh, Earl, and he fainted.
And so Earl, he gave Earl until 10 o'clock the next morning to make up his mind.
Well, it had, the news had come out over radio because we didn't, still didn't have TV.
And we got home, no.
That must be the next day.
It was.
Anyway, he said he had to make up his mind by 10 o'clock the next day.
Well, I had, of course, by then, five children.
Bob was just a baby.
He knew he was premature and all this stuff.
And...
I just knew there was something bad wrong with my health.
And my doctor, who was also our good friend, said, he called me by my silly nickname, so I'm not going to divulge that.
He said, nothing wrong with you, but five kids and no help.
He said, but if you'll feel better, I will send you through the clinic in Fort Worth.
And that was the day that I was to go through the clinic.
So we get up early.
And so on the way to Fort Worth for me to go through the clinic,
Earl and I talked this over, and I said, Earl, you just do what you want to do, because I said, my work's cut out for me with these five children.
And Earl had very decided ideas about how to run a family.
He ran his job and business.
I ran the house and the children.
Anyway, but if anything important, of course, he made the decision.
So we got back, of course, after going through the clinic and then driving home.

It was late, and they had already come out with the fact on the evening news that Earl was the new land commissioner because Earl went in the telephone booth there at the clinic and called Shivers and said he'd take it.
So then we got home, and the house was full of people.
And, you know, Brady's a little town.
Everybody knew us and all.
So we didn't get everybody shooed out until midnight.
Next morning, we got up at 5.30, and it was pouring rain, which was rare.
And the doorbell rang, and I was still in my robe.
And I answered the door, and I told them, come on in.
It was an Angelo paper.
They had a reporter and a photographer, and they came in.
I told them, just make themselves at home.
I had to go get ready.
But we made it.
Now, that's what year?
And you moved then to Austin.
You know, he took office in January.
I said, he took office, and he left me with a pickup.
We had a car and a pickup for the ranks.
He left me with a pickup and five children.
But...
He didn't have time to concentrate on finding a place for us to live.
So we didn't get a house until, to move into until a week before school started.
And so you and the children then moved over there?
Yeah.
And he served for how long?
Well he's, see it was just a two-year term at that time.
And so in one year, I remember the first thing he told me, he said, you know, I don't know who in that office is in cahoots with the commissioner.
So I've got to get somebody around me I know I can trust.
So there was a classmate of his that lived on a farm

between Brady and Rochelle and his wife taught school in Rochelle and they had three kids just scratching out a living so he picked this fella up and he did real well and took him and but that's what he said he had to have somebody around him he knew he could trust
So it was an Aggie classmate of him.
Okay, so, all right, he is appointed in 55, then he's elected to a full term in 56.
Yeah.
A full two-year term.
Yeah.
He had a two-year term to serve, but you had to run before your term was up, you know.
And so, actually, that was...

crazy summer he knew that I couldn't leave the house and go help with a campaign anywhere so we had this big old two-story house with a full basement below that had outside entrance so he decided we'd have campaign headquarters in our house and my job was to serve refreshments every night oh boy and so he had campaigned all over the state and
The top fellows at the land office would come out.
They got out the campaign material.
I didn't have anything to do with that.
But we thought we'd be lucky to have a dozen volunteers a night.
We had 68 or more than that.
I've forgotten exactly.
But anyway, I was making coffee in two little coffee pots.
until one of the fellows that was getting out the campaign material came.
He said, is that the way you've been serving coffee?
I was pouring it up and everything I had.
And I said, yeah.
He said, well, I'll get one from the church.
And so we made coffee in big bunches in.
But anyway, we had two ping pong tables end to end with 25 typewriters going around them in the game room.
See, the big part of the
basement was a big game room and it had a bar and I had a refrigerator and everything and we had a dumb waiter that came down from the kitchen and I could send food down.
Anyway, I have forgotten how long that lasted but seemed like a long time to me.
And you all won the election by a good margin.
Yeah, I've forgotten exactly.
It was kind of tight at first.
We had a little cause for concern, but it came out okay.
And the fellow that he ran against was a good friend of Price Daniels, was county judge over at Tyler.
Mr. Rutter is proceeding to clean up the land office.
And he did it in one year.
Who are the people that he came to...
respect and rely upon most?
Who were his key?
You know one of them.
I think, yes.
Clark Diebel.
That's what I thought.
Yeah, Clark was one of those that discovered the land scandal.
He and a newspaper man, I used to know his name, but I can't think of it today.
I think he was from Quero.
But anyway,
Now, y'all didn't know the Diebels before you got to Austin.
No.
Okay, so he... No, but see, after Clark had been one of the two that discovered the scandals, Earl got...
He was working for the state auditor at that time, and Earl got him to come over and go to work in the land office.
Clark was a fine, fine person.
I agree.
And... Who else?
Well, at the land office?
Yeah, that were key people.
Carl Lynn...
I've lost contact with Carl.
L-I-N-D?
L-I-N-D. L-I-N-D, Carl.
And Arthur Sherlock, and I know where Arthur is, but he's not in very good shape now.
He was the one that was classmate.
S-H-A-R-L-A?
S-H-A-R-L-A-C-H, I think, Sherlock.
He was class of 32, like Earl was.
Anyway, oh, there were others that I knew at the time, but I've kind of forgotten them after all these years.
Do you remember any anecdotes about midnight phone calls or anybody threatening anything during the land office days?
No.
You know, some odd things happened.
Such as?
Like in Brady, there was an attorney there that had something to do with something, I don't know what, but they put a bomb in his car and he almost was killed.
And...

But there was one fella in Brady, it was so funny that he did his best to get Earl not elected, not re-elected because Earl, he had served on the city council and Earl discovered that he had been setting himself up a special utility rate and he was one of the biggest utility rate users in the town of Brady.
Anyway, well, I'm just chattering now.
No, no, no, that's good.
And he had Earl's opponent come out for the... See, G. Raleigh White Downs is a racetrack at Brady, and still is.
Anyway, so this man had Earl's opponent out there and had him introduced at the races and everything.
So I had a call from a friend there in Brady, and she said...
put those five kids in the car and all the campaign material you can get your hands on and get on out here.
Said, Wilson has had your husband's opponent introduced and all.
So the next day I did.
And we put up campaign material between Austin and Brady.
Had a flat on the bridge going across Llano River and ruined a tire.
And I had to try to find a new tire on the 4th of July.
That was kind of hard.
The only place we could find it was open to distribute our campaign material was a beer jar.
And we went in there, my little kids.
